ngland":"Compton Castle, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"1159–":"1159–Overleden","1155–1180":"1155–1180","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1159–Female":"1159–Overleden","1349":"1349","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","1224":"1224","1298":"1298","1155":"1155","abt 1179":"circa 1179","1180":"1180","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Compton Castle, Devon, England":"Compton Castle, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1159–":"1159–Deceased","1155–1180":"1155–1180","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1159–Female":"1159–Deceased","1349":"1349","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","1224":"1224","1298":"1298","1155":"1155","abt 1179":"about 1179","1180":"1180","England":"England, United Kingdom","Compton Castle, Devon, England":"Compton Castle, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gillett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: when pronounced with a soft <i>G</i> (/dʒ/), it is usually from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Gillet</i>, <i>Gilot</i>, <i>Giliot</i>, or <i>Geliot</i>. These are diminutives of <i>Gille</i> or <i>Gilly</i>, which are commonly pet forms of the (often female) name <i>Gilian</i>, <i>Gelian</i> (see   Gillian  ). <i>Gilot</i> and <i>Gillet</i> are also probably pet forms of   Giles  .","English (of Norman origin): when pronounced with hard <i>G</i>, it is more likely from the Middle English personal name <i>Gilot</i>, a borrowing of Old French <i>Guillot</i>, a pet form of   Guillaume   (see   William  ) and a doublet of   Willett  .","English: habitational name from one or other of the numerous minor places called Gillhead, such as those in the parishes of Matterdale, Moresby, Castle Sowerby, and Westward (all Cumberland), formed from Middle English <i>gil(le)</i> ‘ravine, narrow valley’ (Old Norse <i>gil</i>) + <i>hed</i>, <i>heved</i> ‘head’. This would become <i>Gillett</i>, with hard <i>g</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Gillott","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Yorkshire): variant of   Gillett  ."]},{"name":"Gilliatt","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Gillett  ."]},{"name":"Gillette","meanings":["English: variant of   Gillett  , with spelling altered and stress shifted as if it were a modern French name (see 2 below).","French: variant of   Gillet   and, in North America, a variant of its altered form   Gillett  ."]},{"name":"Gillian","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French male and female personal names <i>Gillian</i>, <i>Gilion</i>, <i>Jilian</i>, <i>Gelian</i>, all vernacular forms of Latin <i>Julianus</i> and <i>Juliana</i> (see   Julian  ).","Irish (Antrim): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gileáin</b> ‘son of <i>Gileán</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Gealán</i>, from a diminutive of <i>geal</i> ‘bright, white’."]}]},{"name":"Amy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":56,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":65,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":100,"year":"1259","julianDa